        -:   53:  * \tparam MapOptions specifies the pointer alignment in bytes. It can be: \c #Aligned128, \c #Aligned64, \c #Aligned32, \c #Aligned16, \c #Aligned8 or \c #Unaligned.
        -:   54:  *                The default is \c #Unaligned.
        -:   55:  * \tparam StrideType optionally specifies strides. By default, Map assumes the memory layout
        -:   56:  *                   of an ordinary, contiguous array. This can be overridden by specifying strides.
        -:   57:  *                   The type passed here must be a specialization of the Stride template, see examples below.
        -:   58:  *
        -:   59:  * This class represents a matrix or vector expression mapping an existing array of data.
        -:   60:  * It can be used to let Eigen interface without any overhead with non-Eigen data structures,
        -:   61:  * such as plain C arrays or structures from other libraries. By default, it assumes that the
        -:   62:  * data is laid out contiguously in memory. You can however override this by explicitly specifying
        -:   63:  * inner and outer strides.
        -:   64:  *
        -:   65:  * Here's an example of simply mapping a contiguous array as a \ref TopicStorageOrders "column-major" matrix:
        -:   66:  * \include Map_simple.cpp
        -:   67:  * Output: \verbinclude Map_simple.out
        -:   68:  *
        -:   69:  * If you need to map non-contiguous arrays, you can do so by specifying strides:
        -:   70:  *
        -:   71:  * Here's an example of mapping an array as a vector, specifying an inner stride, that is, the pointer
        -:   72:  * increment between two consecutive coefficients. Here, we're specifying the inner stride as a compile-time
        -:   73:  * fixed value.
        -:   74:  * \include Map_inner_stride.cpp
        -:   75:  * Output: \verbinclude Map_inner_stride.out
        -:   76:  *
        -:   77:  * Here's an example of mapping an array while specifying an outer stride. Here, since we're mapping
        -:   78:  * as a column-major matrix, 'outer stride' means the pointer increment between two consecutive columns.
        -:   79:  * Here, we're specifying the outer stride as a runtime parameter. Note that here \c OuterStride<> is
        -:   80:  * a short version of \c OuterStride<Dynamic> because the default template parameter of OuterStride
        -:   81:  * is  \c Dynamic
        -:   82:  * \include Map_outer_stride.cpp
        -:   83:  * Output: \verbinclude Map_outer_stride.out
        -:   84:  *
        -:   85:  * For more details and for an example of specifying both an inner and an outer stride, see class Stride.
        -:   86:  *
        -:   87:  * \b Tip: to change the array of data mapped by a Map object, you can use the C++
        -:   88:  * placement new syntax:
        -:   89:  *
        -:   90:  * Example: \include Map_placement_new.cpp
        -:   91:  * Output: \verbinclude Map_placement_new.out
        -:   92:  *
        -:   93:  * This class is the return type of PlainObjectBase::Map() but can also be used directly.
        -:   94:  *
        -:   95:  * \sa PlainObjectBase::Map(), \ref TopicStorageOrders
        -:   96:  */
